One way of cell transport is active transport, specifically primary active transport. Primary active transport is as its name suggests, a form of transportation that is active and needs energy put into it for it to function because the transport is occurring against a gradient. To move molecules against their concentration gradient, the use of pumps are necessary. One pump system talked about is the Na+/K+/ATPase pump which transports both Na+ and K+ in opposite directions against their concentration gradients. 
The first step in the Na+/K+/ATPase pump is the binding of three Na+ ions to the protein. Once these ions are within the protein, ATP will attach itself to the protein pump and hydrolyze itself into ADP to activate the conformational change of the protein pump. After the protein has changed shape, the three Na+ ions are released and two K+ ions bind to the protein instead. When these K+ ions bind to the protein, the phosphate left over from the hydrolysis is released and the protein is returned to its original conformation and the process begins again. 
The most important factor affecting the rate of transport in this Na+/K+/ATPase pump is the amount of pumps that are within the cell membrane. This number is the main contributor to the rate of transport because these pumps facilitate the transport. Without these pumps, transport would not be accomplished. Even if the concentrations of both Na+ and K+ ions are increased, the rate will not change unless there are enough pumps available to facilitate transport. Increasing the amount of pumps will in turn directly increase the rate of transport, all other factors will not have the same immense impact as the amount of pumps. The presence of ATP is also an important factor to this cycle, however the hydrolysis of ATP is an all or nothing event. If there are enough molecules of ATP present within the cell the cycle will prosper. Increasing the amount of ATP will not have an impact on the rate of transport after a certain point. Therefore, the amount of pumps available remains to be the biggest factor affecting the rate of transport for the Na+/K+/ATPase pump.

The four classes of biological molecules include carbohydrates, lipids, proteins, and nucleotides and nucleic acids. All four classes are key to composing the structure of the cell structure. Ranking these molecules into the order of their significance proved to be quite difficult as all molecules are key to making up the cell.
 
The most important molecule in regards to cell structure would have to be lipids. This is because lipids create the cell membrane, and without this molecule a cell membrane would not be possible. Lipids come together and create what is called a phospholipid bilayer which make up the entirety of the cell membrane. The bilayer gives the cell the ability to be selective of what enters and exits it, and comes about because the lipid molecules that make up the cell membrane are amphipathic, which means they can be both polar and nonpolar. The outer part of the cell membrane is composed of hydrophilic heads that essentially like being in polar solutions. Whereas the inner part of the membrane is made up of hydrophobic tails that do not like polar solutions. Cholesterol a specific type of lipid also aids in the formation of the cell membrane by preventing hydrophobic interactions from occurring within the hydrophobic tail portion of the bilayer. Cholesterol also decreases fluidity of the membrane which in turn increases its stability, and decreases the movement of water.

Following lipids in importance of cell structure would have to be carbohydrates. Carbohydrates bind to the lipids that make up the plasma membrane, and assist in making up the extracellular surface. One specific carbohydrate that is imperative to cell structure is Glycocalyx. Glycocalyx is a glycoprotein-polysaccharide that covers the cell membrane and assists in holding the cells together with a protective layer, and also functions in cell recognition. In addition to this important role in making up the cell structure carbohydrates are the primary energy sources for cells. Without carbs as an energy source cells would not be able to function in the manner they do.
 
The next molecule of importance would be proteins. Proteins contribute an important role with cell structure in that it gives the plasma membrane it mosaic character, and also support transport between the cell and extracellular fluid. There are two different types of proteins, integral and peripheral. Integral proteins are proteins that are embedded within the phospholipid bilayer which are necessary for the stability of the membrane. If these integral proteins were to be removed the cell itself would be disrupted. Peripheral proteins are those that are loosely attached to the membrane, and typically found on the cytosolic surface. The difference between integral and peripheral proteins are that peripheral proteins can be dissociated from the bilayer and leave the membrane undisturbed, whereas integral proteins once you remove them the membrane will no longer remain.

The molecule I believe that is of least importance for the structure of a cell are nucleotides and nucleic acids. These molecules are used within the cell to transfer energy and also make up all genetic material. These molecules are extremely important for the cell to function, however I feel they do not play a large role structurally as much as the other three biological molecules do.
